e Century of the Farm and the Century of the Fish -- tChapter Twenty-two. The Central Valley Project and the Public Trust Doctrine -- tPart Four. Restoration Efforts. Local Perspectives -- tChapter Twenty-three. Sacramento River Problems and Opportunities -- tChapter Twenty-four. The Salmon Stamp Program -- tChapter Twenty-five. North Coast Salmon and Steelhead and Their Habitat (2) -- tChapter Twenty-six. The CCC's Salmon Restoration Project -- tChapter Twenty-seven. For the Sake of Salmon -- tChapter Twenty-eight. Urban Stream Restoration -- tChapter Twenty-nine. Saving the Steelhead -- tSummary and Conclusions -- tAbbreviations -- tGlossary -- tSuggested Reading -- tSuggested Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMillions upon millions of salmon and steelhead once filled California streams, providing a plentiful and sustainable food resource for the original peoples of the region. But over the years, dams and irrigation diversions have reduced natural spawning habitat from an estimated 6,000 miles to fewer than 300. River pollution has also hit hard at fish populations, which within recent decades have diminished by 80 percent. One species, the San Joaquin River spring chinook, became extinct soon after World War II. Other species are nearly extinct. This volume documents the reasons for the decline; it also offers practical suggestions about how the decline might be reversed. The California salmon story is presented here in human perspective: its broad historical, economic, cultural, and political facets, as well as the biological, are all treated. No comparable work has ever been published, although some of the material has been available for half a century. In the richly varied contributions in this volume, the reader meets Indians whose history is tied to the history of the salmon and steelhead upon which they depend; commercial trollers who see their livelihood and unique lifestyle vanishing; biologists and fishery managers alarmed at the loss of river water habitable by fish and at the effects of hatcheries on native gene pools. Women who fish, conservation-minded citizens, foresters, economists, outdoor writers, engineers, politicians, city youth restoring streambedsall are represented. Their livesand the lives of all Californiansare affected in myriad ways by the fate of California's salmon and steelhead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSalmon fisherieszCalifornia. 0aSteelhead (Fish)zCalifornia. 4aanimal sciences. 4abiology. 4afish. 4afishes. 4aichthyology. 4alife sciences. 4avertebrates. 4azoology. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Zoology / Ichthyology & Herpetology.2bisacsh1 aBarnes, Stanley M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavoren, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDotvnie, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDownie, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Mary-Jo DelVecchio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallock, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHashagen, Ken, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHedgpeth, Joel W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffman, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHooper, William K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubbard, Richard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKier, William M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo